Home IDS

Cheap Network Intrusion Detection

In this post, I will go through my ultra cheap network intrusion detection system (IDS) based on Snort3 I run at home. The idea / goal is very simple:

  • utilize old tech that is gathering dust
  • segregate my workshop network from the home network
  • run an IDS
  • ghetto-rig a network rack
  • use the port-mirroring functionality of my switch outside of testing devices / reverse engineering.

I bet you have old tech lying around at home too. It's too good to get rid of but lacking the hardware resources to do much. In my case this is a Linksys WRT54-GL and an old Thinkpad T-420.

I started by getting OpenWRT running on the Linksys, after that was completed I did the network setup. I ran a cable from my home router to my workshop and connected it to the Linksys WAN port. After configuring the Linksys, I had an internet connection for my devices via it's LAN ports.

Because the Linksys establishes it's own network, my workshop network is segregated from my home network.

Ghetto-Rig Rack

Don't have a rack to put your network devices? Reclaim some wood and build one ;-)

(Thinkpad T-420, Linksys WRT54-GL, Netgear GS108E and an old Cisco switch)

Network Setup

To get an IDS setup going I essentially needed a way to monitor all traffic in my workshop network. For that, I invested ~35 Euros in a switch that allows port mirroring, in my case the Netgear GS108E. That's all for costs. I mainly wanted this switch for reversing/testing devices, so instead of having it lie around idle most of the time the port mirroring functionality is put to use around the clock. My setup looks like this:

I connected one of the router's LAN ports to Port 1 of the switch. My Thinkpad running Snort3 is connected to Port 2 of the switch, which is configured to mirror Ports 1 and 3-8 to Port 2. That way, my Thinkpad receives all of the traffic going on in the network.

Snort Setup

So, now to installing Snort. For my installation, I decided to with Snort3, that means I built everything from source.

Let me give you a walkthrough of the installation.

NOTE: Look out for the version numbers, they might not be the current ones when you're reading this.

# dependencies
apt install build-essential libpcap-dev libpcre3-dev libnet1-dev zlib1g-dev luajit hwloc libdnet-dev libdumbnet-dev bison flex liblzma-dev openssl libssl-dev pkg-config libhwloc-dev cmake cpputest libsqlite3-dev uuid-dev libcmocka-dev libnetfilter-queue-dev libmnl-dev autotools-dev libluajit-5.1-dev libunwind-dev

# get snort and dependencies
wget https://github.com/snort3/snort3/archive/refs/tags/3.1.22.0.tar.gz
wget https://github.com/snort3/libdaq/archive/refs/tags/v3.0.6.tar.gz

# install libDAQ
tar xvf v3.0.6.tar.gz
cd libdaq-3.0.6
./bootstrap
./configure
make
sudo make install

# create symlink
sudo ln -s /usr/local/lib/libdaq.so.3 /lib/

# snort
tar xvf 3.1.22.0.tar.gz
cd snort3-3.1.22.0
sudo mkdir -p /usr/local/snort3
export my_path=/usr/local/snort3
./configure_cmake.sh --prefix=$my_path
cd build
sudo make -j $(nproc) install

sudo mkdir -p /usr/local/snort3

cd build
sudo make -j $(nproc) install

That's it. Snort3 should be installed with the above commands. After navigating to /usr/local/snort3/bin/ you can test the installation by running ./snort --version.

Writing Rules

To actually have Snort3 detect something, rules have to be written and loaded. First the $HOME_NET variable must be set:

# in /usr/local/snort3/etc/snort/snort.lua
$HOME_NET = '192.168.1.0/24'

# make a rules directory
sudo mkdir /usr/local/snort3/etc/snort/rules/

# add simple rule for testing
sudo vim /usr/local/snort3/etc/snort/rules/home.rules
# in /usr/local/snort3/etc/snort/snort.lua
$HOME_NET = '192.168.1.0/24'

# make a rules directory
sudo mkdir /usr/local/snort3/etc/snort/rules/

# add simple rule for testing
sudo vim /usr/local/snort3/etc/snort/rules/home.rules

Add this rule, 192.168.1.1 is the IP of the Linksys.

# when the router is pinged, alert
alert icmp $HOME_NET any -> 192.168.1.1 any (msg:"gateway ping";sid:1;)
# when the router is pinged, alert
alert icmp $HOME_NET any -> 192.168.1.1 any (msg:"gateway ping";sid:1;)

Let's add snort3 to $PATH and try it out!

# add to .bashrc
export PATH="$PATH:/usr/local/snort3/bin"
# run it
sudo ./snort -c ../etc/snort/snort.lua -R ../etc/snort/rules/home.rules -i enp0s25 -A alert_full
# add to .bashrc
export PATH="$PATH:/usr/local/snort3/bin"
# run it
sudo ./snort -c ../etc/snort/snort.lua -R ../etc/snort/rules/home.rules -i enp0s25 -A alert_full

This will log all alerts to the screen.

Now when you connect a device to port 3-8 and ping the gateway at 192.168.1.1, Snort3 will issue an alert:

Now that Snort3 works, more rules can be added to home.rules.

Improvements

  • Instead of logging to the screen logfiles should be utilized, but for checking if everything works correctly and testing rules, printing to the console isn't a bad idea.
  • get a web interface for alerts and rule editing
  • run Snort3 as a service

Conclusion

For ~35€ and a little bit of my time I got an IDS for testing and playing around while reviving some old tech. If you ask me, that's a fair deal, at least for my purposes. I have an IDS and can still use the switch for capturing traffic of devices when I want to test devices, networking programs or whatever.
